@Node "Introduction" "MUI-ASL.guide/Introduction"
@Toc "Main"

Introduction to MUI-ASL
***********************

   Now that MUI applications are so many and widespread, and that even
@{i}Amiga Technologies@{ui} sold some MUI products, several people complain that
the standard ASL library clashes with MUI's ultra-configurable look - and
don't ask for keyboard control.

   In the past years there have been many attempts at providing a
standardized requester library, or at least a good file requester. The
most successful were @{b}ARP@{ub} (1) and @{b}req.library@{ub} (which also provided some
other types of useful requesters), but they didn't survive the advent of
Release 2.0 and ASL.  Today the most widespread alternative is Nico
François' @{b}ReqTools@{ub}, which you may regard as better or worse than ASL
depending on your personal taste, but in the end it's not so different:
you get keyboard control, but the GUI look is still plain GadTools.

   An interesting full-featured replacement for all your file requesters is
Stefan Stuntz's(2) first well-known project, @{b}MagicFileRequester@{ub} (@{b}MFR@{ub}). But
as the name implies it is only a @{i}file requester@{ui} - no font, no screenmode -
and the look is neither configurable nor, in my opinion, very nice. It
also suffers from some bugs that make it pretty unstable.

   These replacements, however, have a problem: they are not @{i}the@{ui} standard.
Only ASL is a standard, because it is part of the OS and will grow with it
(and so will MUI-ASL, I hope).

   After an intresting travel through object-oriented programming and
BOOPSI, I am proud to present @{b}MUI-ASL@{ub}, the MUIfied ASL library.  The
ambitious aim of MUI-ASL is to put a good looking, highly configurable
user interface into ASL, giving many benefits to the innumerable programs
that adopted it for their requesters.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  The AmigaDOS Replacement Project replaced the entire @{b}dos.library@{ub},
most DOS commands and the @{b}CLI@{ub} with much more powerful substitutes, and was
the first widespread file requester. In fact, @{b}dos.library@{ub} V36+ and the ASL
file requester derive from ARP.

   (2)  The author of MUI.


@EndNode

